    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCertain multibyte characters (such as █, ▄, ╓, etc.) are incorrectly treated as occupying 3 screen columns, when their actual display width is only 1.\n\nThis misbehavior shows up in Visual Mode selection (column count is inflated)\n\nThis seems to be caused by Neovim mistakenly using the byte length of the character (UTF-8 encoded) as its display width, instead of its actual screen cell width.\n\nThis command return 1 as expected ':echo strdisplaywidth(\"█\") <-- Will echo 1'. Yet in the status line it suggests that the width is 3.\n\n![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2793117b-e87d-4b67-bf0b-9d56f9ce1a45)\n\n![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/5c36a8ef-8dca-4436-84aa-d625b2db4f05)\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nType `█████` in Neovim and in Normal Mode or Visual Mode select the character\n\n![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2793117b-e87d-4b67-bf0b-9d56f9ce1a45)\n\n![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/5c36a8ef-8dca-4436-84aa-d625b2db4f05)\n\nThe statusline showed that the column is between 18-16 which suggests that the character width is 3\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe statusline should suggests that the character width is 1\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nmaster\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nVIM - Vi IMproved 9.1 (2024 Jan 02, compiled Apr 01 2025 20:12:31)\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nDesktop: Cinnamon v: 6.4.8 Distro: Linux Mint 22.1 Xia\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.1.3\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\ntmux-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo",
